Vheadline
p2
VDedicated to Syama Sastri
p3
sVnews
p4
VAfter rendering the tanam,  Subramaniam sang the kriti in which composer Syama Sastri extols the virtues of his favourite deity Kamakshi.The thaniavarthanam that followed was performed with finesse  by Vypeen Sathish  and Thrikkakare Y. N. Santaram on the mridangam and the ganjira respectively.The concert,  organised by  Sri Swati Tirunal Sangita Sabha. in connection with the Trimurthy Aradhana Festival, was dedicated to Syama Sastri.Subramaniam learnt the early lessons in Carnatic music from the late Parameswara Bhagavathar. He is now learning under Srimushnam V. Rajarao and Padma Rajarao.Subramaniam began his concert with an Ada tala varnam &#8216;Sarasijanabha,&#8217; composed by Vadivelu in Kambhoji. He followed  it with Muthuswami Dikshitar&#8217;s &#8216;Gajananam nyutham&#8217; in Chakravakam.Subramaniam sang with aplomb Syama Sastri&#8217;s popular swarajati comprising  pallavi and charanam. The kriti was &#8216;Kamakshi&#8217; in Bhairavi set to Misra chappu tala.&#8216;Himadrisudhe&#8217; in Kalyani, composed by Syama Sastri, came in for much applause from the rasikas. It was set to Roopaka tala.A Sindubhairavi piece &#8216;Karunai karpagame&#8217; was preceded by the chanting of a sloka.He concluded his concert with a tillana composed by his guru Srimushnam V. Rajarao. In raga Behag, the piece  displayed shades of Nilambari, Varali, Kadanakuthoohalam, Hamsanandi and Sindubhairavi in the form of a ragamalika. Avaneeswaram S.R. Vinu gracefully supported the vocalist  on the violin.The highlights of Subramaniam&#8217;s concert  were  smooth swara sancharam, raga alapana and breath control.
